   "number": "33.1",
   "heading": "Attracting dangerous wildlife",
   "text": "(1) A person must not\n(a) intentionally feed or attempt to feed dangerous wildlife, or\n(b) provide, leave or place an attractant in, on or about any land or premises with the intent of attracting dangerous wildlife.\n(2) A person must not leave or place an attractant in, on or about any land or premises where there are or where there are likely to be people, in a manner in which the attractant could\n(a) attract dangerous wildlife to the land or premises, and\n(b) be accessible to dangerous wildlife.\n(3) Subject to subsections (5) and (6), a person who contravenes subsection (1) or (2) commits an offence.\n(4) If an offence under this section continues for more than one day, separate fines, each not exceeding the maximum fine for that offence, may be imposed for each day the offence continues.\n(5) A person does not contravene subsection (1) (b) or (2) by providing, leaving or placing an attractant in, on or about any land or premises for the purposes of hunting or trapping wildlife in accordance with all other applicable provisions of this Act and the regulations.\n(6) A person does not contravene subsection (2)\n(a) by conducting a farm operation, as defined in section 1 of the Farm Practices Protection (Right to Farm) Act , if the person\n(i) conducts the farm operation on, in or over land anywhere in British Columbia, and\n(ii) meets the requirements set out in section 2 (2) (a) and (c) of that Act, or\n(b) by operating a facility for the disposal of waste, that is operated in accordance with the Environmental Management Act by a municipality, as defined in section 1 (1) of that Act.\n(7) For the purposes of this section, \"leave\" , in relation to a person who is an owner, tenant or occupant of land or premises, includes to fail to remove an attractant from or to allow an attractant to remain in, on or about that land or those premises."
  },
  {
   "id": "wildlife-s34",
   "part": "Part 1 — General Provisions",
   "division": null,
   "number": "34",
   "heading": "Birds, nests and eggs",
   "text": "A person commits an offence if the person, except as provided by regulation, possesses, takes, injures, molests or destroys\n(a) a bird or its egg,\n(b) the nest of an eagle, peregrine falcon, gyrfalcon, osprey, heron or burrowing owl, or\n(c) the nest of a bird not referred to in paragraph (b) when the nest is occupied by a bird or its egg."
  },
  {
   "id": "wildlife-s35",
   "part": "Part 1 — General Provisions",
   "division": null,
   "number": "35",
   "heading": "Retrieval of wildlife killed",
   "text": "(1) In this section, \"dwelling place\" does not include a temporary or seasonal camp.\n(2) A person commits an offence if the person hunts wildlife and kills or injures that wildlife and fails to make every reasonable effort to\n(a) retrieve the wildlife, and if it is alive to kill it and include it in his or her bag limit, and\n(b) remove the edible portions of the carcass of game to the person's normal dwelling place or to a meatcutter or the owner or operator of a cold storage plant,\nunless exempted by regulation."
  },
  {
   "id": "wildlife-s36",
   "part": "Part 1 — General Provisions",
   "division": null,
   "number": "36",
   "heading": "Possession of carcass",
   "text": "(1) A person who possesses the carcass of any wildlife, whether or not the carcass has been divided, without leaving attached the parts required by regulation to be left attached, commits an offence.\n(2) Subsection (1) only applies until the earlier of the following:\n(a) the carcass is given to a meatcutter or the owner or operator of a cold storage plant to be recorded in accordance with section 71,\n(b) the carcass arrives at the person's normal dwelling place and is butchered and stored there for consumption on the premises, or\n(c) the carcass is presented to an employee of the ministry for which the minister is responsible or other person specified by the Lieutenant Governor in Council for inspection."
  },
  {
   "id": "wildlife-s37",
   "part": "Part 1 — General Provisions",
   "division": null,
   "number": "37",
   "heading": "Transportation of wildlife",
   "text": "A person who ships or transports in British Columbia, or engages another person to ship or transport in British Columbia, wildlife or fish or parts of them, except as provided by regulation, commits an offence."
  },
  {
   "id": "wildlife-s38",
   "part": "Part 1 — General Provisions",
   "division": null,
   "number": "38",
   "heading": "Failure to provide information",
   "text": "A person who fails, on the request of an officer, to state correctly the locality where and the date on which wildlife or fish in the person's possession was killed, taken or caught by the person or came into his or her possession, commits an offence."
  },
  {
   "id": "wildlife-s39",
   "part": "Part 1 — General Provisions",
   "division": null,
   "number": "39",
   "heading": "Agricultural and cleared land",
   "text": "(1) A person commits an offence if the person, without the consent of the owner, lessee or occupier of land,\n(a) hunts over or traps in or on cultivated land, or\n(b) hunts over Crown land that is subject to a grazing lease while the land is occupied by livestock.\n(2) This section does not affect the Trespass Act ."
  },
  {
   "id": "wildlife-s40",
   "part": "Part 1 — General Provisions",
   "division": null,
   "number": "40",
   "heading": "Power to prohibit hunting or trapping",
   "text": "(1) Despite anything in this Act or the regulations or the privileges conferred by a licence or limited entry hunting authorization, the minister may, by regulation, prohibit a person or a class of persons from\n(a) hunting or trapping, or\n(b) using a method of hunting or trapping\nin a defined area for a period the minister considers necessary for the proper management of wildlife in that area.\n(2) Despite anything in this Act or the regulations, the minister may, by regulation, allow a person or a class of persons to hunt or trap in a defined area for a period the minister considers necessary for the proper management of wildlife in that area."
  },
  {
   "id": "wildlife-s40.1",
   "part": "Part 1 — General Provisions",
   "division": null,
   "number": "40.1",
   "heading": "Issue of trapping licence",
   "text": "A regional manager may issue a trapping licence to a person who is a citizen of Canada or a permanent resident of Canada."
  },
  {
   "id": "wildlife-s41",
   "part": "Part 1 — General Provisions",
   "division": null,
   "number": "41",
   "heading": "Prohibition within a trapline",
   "text": "A person commits an offence if the person sets a trap for, hunts, kills, takes or captures a fur bearing animal in an area of British Columbia unless the person\n(a) is a registered holder of the trapline for that area,\n(b) has written permission of a registered holder of the trapline for that area,\n(c) is the owner or occupier of the land,\n(d) has written permission from the owner or occupier of the land, or\n(e) holds a permit to trap that is required by regulation."
  },
  {
   "id": "wildlife-s42",
   "part": "Part 1 — General Provisions",
   "division": null,
   "number": "42",
   "heading": "Registration of traplines",
   "text": "(1) A regional manager, or a person authorized by the regional manager, may grant registration of a trapline on Crown land to a person who is, or to a group of persons each of whom is,\n(a) 19 years of age or older, and\n(b) a citizen of Canada or a permanent resident of Canada.\n(2) A person or group of persons must not be granted registration of more than one trapline unless\n(a) the traplines are contiguous,\n(b) the person or group of persons has submitted to the regional manager a fur management plan, and\n(c) the regional manager has approved the fur management plan.\n(3) Registration of a trapline or traplines in the name of more than one person creates a tenancy in common.\n(4) If a holder of the traplines for which a fur management plan was submitted does not observe the undertakings given in the plan, the regional manager may take action under section 61.\n(5) Registration of a trapline does not\n(a) give the holder of the trapline any proprietary rights in wildlife, or\n(b) restrict the rights of another person\n(i) to hunt, or\n(ii) to capture wildlife if authorized by the regulations or a permit."
  },
  {
   "id": "wildlife-s43",
   "part": "Part 1 — General Provisions",
   "division": null,
   "number": "43",
   "heading": "Use of trapline",
   "text": "(1) A person must not hold a registered trapline unless the person complies with the regulations and the conditions of his or her licence.\n(2) Despite a regulation or a condition of a licence requiring the holder of a trapline to carry on active trapping, the regional manager may authorize the holder of a registered trapline to temporarily discontinue the use or part of the use of the trapline for a period not exceeding 2 years."
  },
  {
   "id": "wildlife-s44",
   "part": "Part 1 — General Provisions",
   "division": null,
   "number": "44",
   "heading": "Leaving traps set",
   "text": "A person who leaves a trap set after the last day of the open season for the trapping of fur bearing animals commits an offence."
  },
  {
   "id": "wildlife-s45",
   "part": "Part 1 — General Provisions",
   "division": null,
   "number": "45",
   "heading": "Disputes",
   "text": "If a dispute arises as to priority of rights respecting any trapline, the matter must, at the request of a party to the dispute, be determined by the regional manager, who may alter, eliminate or reassign part or all of a trapline."
  },
  {
   "id": "wildlife-s46",
   "part": "Part 1 — General Provisions",
   "division": null,
   "number": "46",
   "heading": "Interference with traps",
   "text": "A person who knowingly damages or interferes with a lawfully set trap commits an offence."
  },
  {
   "id": "wildlife-s47",
   "part": "Part 1 — General Provisions",
   "division": null,
   "number": "47",
   "heading": "Non-residents and big game",
   "text": "A person commits an offence if the person hunts big game unless he or she\n(a) is a resident, or\n(b) is accompanied by\n(i) a guide licensed under this Act,\n(i.1) an assistant guide issued a written authorization under section 48 (1.2), or\n(ii) a person who holds a permit under section 70 (1) (a) allowing him or her to accompany the hunter."
  },
  {
   "id": "wildlife-s48",
   "part": "Part 1 — General Provisions",
   "division": null,
   "number": "48",
   "heading": "Requirements and offences for guide outfitters and assistant guides",
   "text": "(1) A person, other than a person who guides for game as an assistant guide in accordance with this Act, commits an offence if the person acts as a guide for game, or offers to act as a guide for game, unless the person\n(a) holds a guide outfitter licence,\n(b) [Repealed 2014-7-68.]\n(c) holds another licence to guide for game, or\n(d) accompanies or assists a person to hunt game birds or small game on land other than Crown land.\n(1.1) A guide outfitter may employ a person as an assistant guide to guide for game on behalf of the guide outfitter only if the guide outfitter ensures that\n(a) the person meets the prescribed qualifications, if any,\n(b) the person is not prohibited under this Act from applying for employment as an assistant guide,\n(c) the person is not prohibited under this Act from guiding as an assistant guide, and\n(d) the terms of employment are consistent with any conditions or restrictions imposed under this Act on the person and any prescribed requirements referred to in subsection (2.1) (h).\n(1.2) A guide outfitter must promptly issue to an assistant guide written authorization, in the prescribed manner and form and with the prescribed content,\n(a) on employing the assistant guide under subsection (1.1), and\n(b) whenever a change in prescribed circumstances occurs.\n(1.3) A guide outfitter must, in relation to assistant guides employed by the guide outfitter under subsection (1.1),\n(a) create and maintain any records required by the regulations,\n(b) keep any records referred to in paragraph (a) for a prescribed period, and\n(c) provide any records referred to in paragraph (a) to an officer on request.\n(2) A person who holds a guide outfitter licence commits an offence if the person employs an assistant guide to guide for game and contravenes any of the provisions of subsections (1.1) to (1.3).\n(2.1) A person must not guide for game as an assistant guide unless the person\n(a) meets the prescribed qualifications, if any,\n(b) is employed under subsection (1.1) as an assistant guide by a guide outfitter,\n(c) has been issued written authorization under subsection (1.2) by the guide outfitter referred to in paragraph (b) of this subsection,\n(d) at all times when guiding for game as an assistant guide, carries\n(i) the written authorization referred to in paragraph (c), and\n(ii) any other prescribed documentation that is issued, in the prescribed manner and form and with the prescribed content, to the assistant guide,\n(e) produces the written authorization referred to in paragraph (c) and other documentation referred to in paragraph (d) (ii) on the request of an officer or a person the assistant guide is guiding for game,\n(f) is not prohibited under this Act from guiding as an assistant guide,\n(g) complies with any conditions or restrictions imposed under this Act on the assistant guide, and\n(h) meets the prescribed requirements, if any.\n(2.2) A person guiding for game as an assistant guide commits an offence if the person fails to meet any of the requirements under subsection (2.1).\n(2.3) Subsections (1.1) to (1.3) and (2) to (2.2) do not apply in respect of a person who guides as an assistant guide if the person accompanies or assists another person to hunt game birds or small game on land other than Crown land.\n(3) A guide outfitter must be present in his or her guiding area during a majority of the time when his or her assistant guides are guiding for game.\n(4) If a guide outfitter fails to comply with subsection (3), a regional manager may take action under section 61."
  },
  {
   "id": "wildlife-s49",
   "part": "Part 1 — General Provisions",
   "division": null,
   "number": "49",
   "heading": "Compulsory angling guide licence",
   "text": "(1) A person commits an offence if the person acts as a guide for fish, or offers to act as a guide for fish, unless the person\n(a) holds an angling guide licence, or\n(b) holds an assistant angling guide licence.\n(2) A person who holds an angling guide licence commits an offence if the person employs another person to guide for fish and that other person does not hold an assistant angling guide licence.\n(3) An angling guide must\n(a) be present in one of the regions specified in the angling guide's licence, or\n(b) if specific waters or a specific area is authorized in the angling guide's licence, be present on or near those waters or in that area, in the manner specified on the angling guide's licence\nduring substantially all of the times when assistant angling guides employed by the angling guide are guiding for fish.\n(4) If an angling guide fails to comply with subsection (3), a regional manager may take action under section 61.\n(5) An angling guide who guides for fish elsewhere than on the waters or in the area authorized by the angling guide's licence commits an offence.\n(6) An assistant angling guide who guides for fish elsewhere than on the waters or in the area authorized by the licence of the angling guide employing the assistant angling guide commits an offence."
  },
  {
   "id": "wildlife-s50",
   "part": "Part 1 — General Provisions",
   "division": null,
   "number": "50",
   "heading": "Applicants to know Act",
   "text": "An applicant for a guide outfitter licence must satisfy a regional manager that he or she possesses a working knowledge of this Act and the regulations."
  },
  {
   "id": "wildlife-s51",
   "part": "Part 1 — General Provisions",
   "division": null,
   "number": "51",
   "heading": "Issue of guide outfitter licence",
   "text": "(1) A regional manager\n(a) may issue a guide outfitter licence to a person if all of the following apply:\n(i) the person is a citizen of Canada or a permanent resident of Canada;\n(ii) the person has public liability insurance prescribed by regulation;\n(iii) the person has other qualifications prescribed by regulation, and\n(b) must issue a guide outfitter licence to a person if the person is a person to whom the regional manager is obliged under the Labour Mobility Act to issue a guide outfitter licence.\n(2) A guide outfitter licence authorizes the holder to guide persons to hunt only for those species of game and in the area described in the licence.\n(3) If an area is part of a guiding territory assigned in a guiding territory certificate, the regional manager may not issue a guide outfitter licence under subsection (1) authorizing a person to guide in the area unless the person provides proof, satisfactory to the regional manager, that the person has the consent of the holder of the guiding territory certificate."
  },
  {
   "id": "wildlife-s52",
   "part": "Part 1 — General Provisions",
   "division": null,
   "number": "52",
   "heading": "Issue of angling guide licences",
   "text": "(1) A regional manager may issue an angling guide licence to a person who\n(a) is a citizen of Canada or a permanent resident of Canada,\n(b) has public liability insurance and other qualifications prescribed by regulation, and\n(c) has submitted an angling guide operating plan that has been approved by the regional manager.\n(2) If the holder of an angling guide licence does not observe the undertakings given by the holder in an angling guide operating plan, the regional manager may take action under section 61.\n(3) Until the publication by the Recreational Fisheries Branch of a plan for managing guiding for fish and angling on a stream or lake or in an area of British Columbia, the minister may order the regional manager to restrict the issue of angling guide licences or endorsements for that stream, lake or area to persons who, on the date of the order, hold an angling guide licence or endorsement for that stream, lake or area.\n(4) If a plan referred to in subsection (3) for a stream, lake or area specified in an order of the minister is not published within the period of 18 months after the date of the order, the order ceases to have any effect on the expiry of that period."
  },
  {
   "id": "wildlife-s53",
   "part": "Part 1 — General Provisions",
   "division": null,
   "number": "53",
   "heading": "Restrictions on guiding for fish and angling",
   "text": "(1) The Lieutenant Governor in Council, by regulation, may do one or more of the following:\n(a) limit the number of angling guides permitted to guide for fish on a stream or lake or in an area of British Columbia during a specified period;\n(b) limit the number of angler days on which members of a class of persons may be guided for fish on a stream or lake or in an area of British Columbia during a specified period;\n(c) limit the number of\n(i) clients an angling guide may guide for fish, and\n(ii) assistant angling guides an angling guide may employ\non a stream or lake or in an area of British Columbia on any day during a specified period;\n(d) limit the number of angler days on which members of a class of persons may angle without a guide on a stream or lake or in an area of British Columbia during a specified period;\n(e) provide for the selection of applicants for angler days by a lottery or a booking system or by any other means;\n(f) provide for the issue of licences specifying the number of days on which a person may angle on a stream or lake or in an area of British Columbia;\n(g) provide for the allocation of angler day quotas to and among angler guides and for the disposal of angler day quotas by auction or tender or any other means;\n(h) provide for the suspension, cancellation or variation of an angler day quota;\n(i) prohibit or regulate the transfer of an angling licence or angler day quota or both;\n(j) prescribe the information and undertakings to be included in an angling guide operating plan;\n(k) impose or provide for requirements respecting the use of angler day quotas to ensure that the use of an angler day quota is not restricted to a club or other group of persons;\n(l) prohibit or regulate in relation to the periods of time during which members of a class of persons may angle on a stream or lake or in an area of British Columbia, including prescribing different periods for different classes, including, without limitation, classes based on age.\n(2) For the purpose of subsection (1) (e), (g), (h), (i), (j), (k) and (l), the Lieutenant Governor in Council may make different regulations for different classes of streams or lakes or for different areas of British Columbia.\n(3) A regulation made under this section may\n(a) provide for the attachment of an angler day quota to, or for the reduction or cancellation of an angler day quota attached to, an angling guide licence issued before or after this section or the regulation comes into force, and\n(b) impose limitations, restrictions and requirements relating to guiding for fish on an angling guide, even though the angling guide's licence was issued before this section or the regulation comes into force."
  },
  {
   "id": "wildlife-s54",
   "part": "Part 1 — General Provisions",
   "division": null,
   "number": "54",
   "heading": "Issue of assistant angling guide licence",
   "text": "(1) The regional manager or the regional manager's designate may issue an assistant angling guide licence to a person if all of the following apply:\n(a) the person is a citizen of Canada or a permanent resident of Canada;\n(b) the person is 19 years of age or older;\n(c) the person has other qualifications prescribed by regulation.\n(2) An assistant angling guide licence is valid only while the holder of the licence carries a record, signed by an angling guide, that indicates that the angling guide employs the holder as an assistant angling guide."
  },
  {
   "id": "wildlife-s55",
   "part": "Part 1 — General Provisions",
   "division": null,
   "number": "55",
   "heading": "Guide reports",
   "text": "(1) A guide outfitter must\n(a) immediately after a hunt is concluded, complete and sign a guide report in the form specified by the director, and\n(b) immediately after signing the completed guide report, give a copy of the report to each hunter guided on the hunt.\n(c) [Repealed 2011-27-32.]\n(2) A guide outfitter who contravenes subsection (1) commits an offence.\n(3) A guide outfitter may comply with subsection (1) by having an agent of the guide outfitter complete and sign the guide report, and give a copy of that report, on behalf of the guide outfitter."
  },
