   "division": null,
   "number": "56",
   "heading": "Guiding unlicensed hunters and anglers",
   "text": "(1) A guide who guides a hunter for game commits an offence unless the hunter holds a hunting licence and any other required licence.\n(2) A person who guides an angler for fish commits an offence unless the angler holds an angling licence and any other required licence."
  },
  {
   "id": "wildlife-s57",
   "part": "Part 1 — General Provisions",
   "division": null,
   "number": "57",
   "heading": "Repealed",
   "text": "[Repealed 2008-33-17.]"
  },
  {
   "id": "wildlife-s58",
   "part": "Part 1 — General Provisions",
   "division": null,
   "number": "58",
   "heading": "Non-use of waters or area by angling guide",
   "text": "If an angling guide does not guide or states that he or she does not intend to guide anglers in a year,\n(a) the angling guide may apply to the regional manager for permission to temporarily discontinue or partially discontinue the use of the waters or area authorized by his or her angling guide licence, or\n(b) the regional manager may review the angling guide's operation and, after affording him or her an opportunity to be heard, the regional manager may suspend, cancel or refuse to renew the angling guide's licence."
  },
  {
   "id": "wildlife-s59",
   "part": "Part 1 — General Provisions",
   "division": null,
   "number": "59",
   "heading": "Guiding territory certificate",
   "text": "(1) A regional manager may issue a guiding territory certificate to a person who, or to a group of persons each of whom,\n(a) [Repealed 2014-7-70.]\n(b) in the case of an individual, is 19 years of age or older, and\n(c) has the qualifications prescribed by regulation, if any.\n(2) A guiding territory certificate issued under this Act must be issued in a manner and form, if any, and with the conditions, if any, specified by the director.\n(3) Subject to a permit issued under section 70 (1) (b), a guiding territory certificate grants to the holder the exclusive control over guiding privileges in the area described in the certificate for the period stated in the certificate, which may not exceed 25 years.\n(4) The issuance of a guiding territory certificate to more than one person creates a tenancy in common in the rights granted by the certificate.\n(5) If a guiding territory certificate is issued to more than one person, the guiding territory certificate must\n(a) identify a person as the agent of the holders of the certificate, and\n(b) specify the interest held in the certificate by each holder of the certificate.\n(6) A regional manager may rely on information provided in an application or submission made by the agent identified in the guiding territory certificate as if that information were provided or that application or submission were made by all the holders of the certificate.\n(7) A regional manager may, on application by the holder of the guiding territory certificate, issue a new guiding territory certificate for a period not exceeding 25 years if\n(a) more than 5 years have elapsed since the date of issue of a guiding territory certificate issued before this subsection comes into force, or\n(b) more than 3/5 of the period of a guiding territory certificate issued after this subsection comes into force has elapsed."
  },
  {
   "id": "wildlife-s59.1",
   "part": "Part 1 — General Provisions",
   "division": null,
   "number": "59.1",
   "heading": "Non-use of guiding territory",
   "text": "(1) On application by the holder of a guiding territory certificate who does not intend to consent to guiding in a year in the guiding territory described in the guiding territory certificate, the regional manager may give permission for the temporary or partial discontinuance of the use of that guiding territory for guiding.\n(2) If, in the opinion of the regional manager, there is no guiding in a year in a guiding territory described in a guiding territory certificate,\n(a) the regional manager may review the operation of the holder of the guiding territory certificate, and\n(b) after affording the holder an opportunity to be heard, the regional manager may suspend, cancel or refuse to renew the guiding territory certificate."
  },
  {
   "id": "wildlife-s60",
   "part": "Part 1 — General Provisions",
   "division": null,
   "number": "60",
   "heading": "Quotas",
   "text": "(1) If a regional manager issues a guide outfitter licence, the regional manager may attach a quota as a condition of the licence and may vary the quota for a subsequent licence year.\n(2) If a guide outfitter has a quota assigned as a condition of his or her guide outfitter licence and allows his or her clients to kill game to the extent that the number killed exceeds the quota assigned to the guide outfitter, the regional manager may reduce or take away his or her quota for a period and may take action under section 61."
  },
  {
   "id": "wildlife-s61",
   "part": "Part 1 — General Provisions",
   "division": null,
   "number": "61",
   "heading": "Action if conditions of licence, certificate or registration not fulfilled",
   "text": "(1) If a person holds, held within the last year or applies to renew, a guide outfitter's licence, guiding territory certificate or another licence to guide for game, angling guide licence, assistant angling guide licence, trapping licence, fur trader's licence or registration of a trapline and the person is convicted of an offence under this Act or does not comply with the conditions contained in or restrictions imposed on his or her licence, certificate or registration, or for another cause that the regional manager considers reasonable, the regional manager may conduct a hearing to determine whether the person should continue to enjoy the privileges afforded him or her by the licence or certificate or by having the registration and may do one or more of the following:\n(a) suspend, cancel or refuse to issue or renew the person's licence, certificate or registration;\n(b) amend the licence, certificate or registration to specify a different area in which the person may operate;\n(c) in the case of a guide outfitter,\n(i) amend the licence to further limit the numbers, age and sex of game in respect of which the person may guide,\n(ii) prohibit the person from guiding as an assistant guide for a period of time the regional manager specifies,\n(iii) specify an area in which the person may not guide as an assistant guide for a period of time the regional manager specifies, and\n(iv) impose conditions or restrictions on the person, in respect of guiding as an assistant guide, that the regional manager considers appropriate for a period of time the regional manager specifies;\n(d) amend the licence, certificate or registration to require the person to meet other conditions or restrictions that the regional manager considers appropriate;\n(e) in the case of an angling guide, reduce or cancel an angler day quota attached to that person's licence.\n(1.1) If a person is guiding as an assistant guide or was guiding as an assistant guide in the past year and the person is convicted of an offence under this Act, or for another cause that the regional manager considers reasonable, the regional manager may conduct a hearing to determine whether the person should be allowed to continue to guide as an assistant guide and may do one or more of the following:\n(a) prohibit the person from guiding as an assistant guide for a period of time the regional manager specifies;\n(b) specify an area in which the person may not guide as an assistant guide for a period of time the regional manager specifies;\n(c) impose conditions or restrictions on the person, in respect of guiding as an assistant guide, that the regional manager considers appropriate for a period of time the regional manager specifies.\n(2) The person in respect of whom the hearing under subsection (1) or (1.1) is to be conducted must be given reasonable notice of the time and place for the hearing.\n(2.1) [Repealed 2016-11-43.]\n(3) A hearing conducted under subsection (1) or (1.1) must be held in public unless the minister orders that the hearing be held in private.\n(4) If notice of a hearing under subsection (1) is given to the holder of a licence, certificate or registered trapline and the licence or certificate expires or the registration ceases before the regional manager conducts the hearing or makes a determination under that subsection, the regional manager\n(a) may proceed to hear and determine the matter, and\n(b) is not obliged to renew or consider renewal of the licence or certificate or grant registration of the trapline until the earlier of the following:\n(i) the end of the 30 day period immediately after the licence or certificate expires or the registration ceases;\n(ii) the regional manager makes the determination after the hearing is held.\n(5) Despite subsection (4), if the hearing is delayed at the request of the holder of the licence, certificate or registered trapline, the regional manager is not obliged to consider renewing the licence or certificate or granting the registration of the trapline until the regional manager makes the determination after the hearing is held."
